<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I guess President Bush was paying attention during all those corporate scandals. After all, his latest budget strategy is pure Enron: If you leave $87 billion in spending out of the budget, the rest of your balance sheet will look a lot better—at least until the bill comes due. <br>
<br>
With the administration's encouragement, Congress will consider the request as a &quot;supplemental&quot; spending bill—in other words, as funds to be spent on top of whatever it approves for fiscal 2004. At a time when deficits have suddenly re-emerged as a campaign issue, this distinction is important because it enables the president and Congress to continue their charade of fiscal discipline. As Chris Edwards, director of fiscal policy at the Cato Institute, notes, it has become a kind of game. Every year the administration announces it will hold discretionary spending to a 4 percent increase, and every year the Bushies and Congress gleefully ignore their vow. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2050<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/18/03 10:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: You patriot, you</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It amazes how pro-Israeli the US population is (as a general).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, I can't speak for all of America, but I can explain why I am pro-Israeli.<br>
<br>
I remember in high school taking an Asian and Middle Easter Studies elective, in which I learned the history of the conflict in the Middle East.  Coming out of that course, I was sympathetic to both the Israelis and the Palestinians, perhaps slightly more sympathetic to the Palestinians.<br>
<br>
Since that time, terrorism has shifted my sympathies entirely to the Israelis.  Yasser Arafat, the leader of the Palestinians, still supports terrorists.  Every other day you see another innocent Israeli child or civilian killed by Palestinians.  Under Barak, the Israelis put forth an extremely generous offer that would have allowed for the creation of an independent Palestinian state.  The Palestinians turned him down.<br>
<br>
After that point, and after listening to the Palestinians, I became convinced that the Palestinians do not in fact want to compromise.  They will settle for nothing less than the annihilation of Israel.  They still employ terrorism as a means of achieving their ends.<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, I still hope for peace in the middle east.  However, I would not support witholding aid to Israel or trying to force them to negotiate until terrorism ceases and Arafat is removed from power.  I still think we should try to negotiate peace, but as long as the Palestinian leadership continues to support terrorism, I will consider the Israelis the wronged party.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=merraharvaz>MerraharVaz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 347<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/19/03 4:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: You patriot, you</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Under Barak, the Israelis put forth an extremely generous offer that would have allowed for the creation of an independent Palestinian state. The Palestinians turned him down.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Of course, that was AFTER Oslo Accord, in which there was already agreement on an independent Palestinian state. Netanyanu broke those accords (interestingly enough, the UN resolution to condemn Israel for breaking it was veto'd by the US). And by the way, the &quot;generous&quot; offer would require the Palestinians to split up in 3 or 4 parts, without the right to secure their own border and without rights to their own airspace.<br>
<br>
When Netanyanu came to power, he was deadset on getting rid of Oslo. If I remember correctly, the terrorist actions vs Israel began to increase when he closed access to a bridge that the Palestinians used to access one of their holy sites in Jerusalem. Technically, not even a violation of the accords, of course, but it was totally unnecessary and he did it with only one goal in mind : angering the Palestinians.<br>
<br>
I believe the Palestinians were the first to start the killing again. But that was after the Israeli's bulldozered their homes.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yasser Arafat, the leader of the Palestinians, still supports terrorists.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
During Oslo, Arafat was unpopular among his own people. Hamas didn't acknowledge him as leader. He had no power whatsoever on the terrorists. I do believe he could've done more to hunt them down. I also believe that would've been the end of his power, since his position was already shaky.<br>
<br>
In the 90's Arrafat was a supporter of the peace. He wanted peace for his people and he (along with the rest of the world) thought he had it in Oslo. Currently, I'm not sure whether he is a positive influence on the peace process. After Israel besieged him, he became a martyr and immensily popular. It might be that this popularity corrupted him - his failure to cooperate with Abbas was very damaging to the peace.<br>
<br>
Hmm, that was longwinded (my middle name), but tell me ... how do you come to the conclusion he is supporting the terrorists ?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>to force them to negotiate until terrorism ceases <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The terrorists don't want peace. They made that clear since Oslo. You might as well blow every Palestinian to kingdom come, if you are gonna blame the Palestinians as a whole for the terrorists. Hamas wants to make the whole country free of Jews... they're not exactly reasonable. They are going to continue, peace treaty or not.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I will consider the Israelis the wronged party.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That kind of thinking is exactly what is blocking the peace. Israel want eye-for-eye ... Although I believe in this concept, it is only escalating the violence. The support for terrorist actions against Israel is high among the Palestinian people. It will go down slowly, but will be fueled by every Israel action vs Palestinians. If there is ever going to be peace, one of the parties has to stop wanting revenge. I have little hope in that party being Hamas, but the mistake here is blaming all the Palestinians for the actions of a terrorist organisation.<br>
